{"name":"How Money Floats","id":22,"content":"<p>https://economicprinciples.org/</p>\n\n<h2>Financial Bank Structure:</h2>\n\n<p>Front Office, Middle Office, and Back Office.<br />\nFront Office divisions: Investment Banking, Sales and Trading, Commercial Banking, merchant banking&nbsp;</p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li>Investment banking to help clients raise money in capital markets, and help companies on mergers and acquisitions.</li>\n\t<li>Sales and Trading to buy/sell (on behalf of bank and it&#39;s clients) financial products.</li>\n\t<li>Research division to review companies and write reports about future earning prospects, which other financial professionals buy.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>Middle Office includes Risk Management, Financial control, corporate treasury, corporate strategy and compliance, to keep a tab on risk in which investment bank may be involved.</p>\n\n<p>Back Office includes Operations and Technology provided to Front office to make money.</p>\n\n<p>Companies hire Investment Banks to act as a middleman between company and public. IB determines the value and riskiness of business in order to price, underwrite and then sell new bonds. Banks also write other securities like Stocks through and IPO or secondary public offering.</p>\n\n<p>Investment Bank may also act as Market Maker, that is they will buy share of company even if they do not have a seller lined up, to create a market.</p>\n\n<p>Institutional Investors such as Mutual Funds, Pension Funds, Hedge Funds &nbsp;use Investment Banks in order to trade securities.</p>\n\n<p>Investment Bank Functions: Giving Advice, Investment Mgt. , Providing financing, Trading, Research.</p>\n\n<h1>&nbsp;</h1>\n","authorId":null,"subject":"finance","tags":[""],"img":null,"summary":null,"lastUpdated":null}